('public_domain', 'Will Rogers', 1879, 1935, 'vaudeville_film', 'Folksy satire, homespun irony, plain-spoken irony—disguises sharp political insight behind Oklahoma charm, improvised timing', '"I don''t make jokes. I just watch the government and report the facts" — 1923 column. "There are two theories to arguing with a woman. Neither works."', 'William Penn Adair Rogers (1879–1935) rose from vaudeville rope-trick performer to national sage. Wrote 4,000+ newspaper columns, appeared in dozens of silent/sound films.'),

('public_domain', 'Eddie Cantor', 1892, 1964, 'vaudeville_film', 'High-energy satire, musical comedy, comic exuberance—turns anxiety into rhythm, rolling eyes and relentless patter, topical speed like jazz riffs', '"I''m not nervous—I just haven''t stopped trembling since 1913" — Ziegfeld Follies 1921 stage patter.', 'Edward Israel Iskowitz (1892–1964) was New York vaudevillian who became first multimedia star—Broadway, records, radio, early sound film with manic singing style.'),

('public_domain', 'Fanny Brice', 1891, 1951, 'vaudeville_film', 'Character comedy, emotional farce, character immersion—built entire personas with total conviction, mixed pathos and parody', '"I''m wearing second-hand hats / Second-hand clothes / That''s why they call me Second-Hand Rose" — 1921 hit, delivered with mock-melancholy resilience.', 'Fania Borach (1891–1951) was Ziegfeld Follies star combining vocal virtuosity with flawless comic character work, most famously child "Baby Snooks."');

